,"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a one month history of progressively worsening dyspnoea and right-sided lower chest pain, particularly during exercise. She has no weight loss, anorexia or fatigue. She has a history of myocardial infarction two years ago and is currently post-menopausal and receiving hormone replacement therapy. She has chronic bilateral knee joint pain, for which she takes daily naproxen. She has a two-pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her vital signs are: blood pressure 130/90mmHg, pulse rate 99/min, temperature 37.7\u00b0C, respiratory rate 25/min, and oxygen saturation 94% on room air. She has decreased breath sounds in the right lower lobe with crackles. On examination of her lower limbs, her right calf is more swollen than her left.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray demonstrates a right-sided pleural effusion measuring approximately 500mL. A diagnostic pleural tap is performed. The pleural fluid is blood stained, exudative, and microscopy demonstrated red blood cells. Culture of the pleural fluid is negative, and the cytology does not show any malignant cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause for her pleural effusion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lung cancer","Cardiac failure","Pulmonary infarction","Rheumatoid arthritis","Pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe underlying cause of a unilateral pleural effusion in this patient is most likely \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary infarction\u003C/strong\u003E because of the presence of an exudative, blood-stained pleural fluid with red blood cells seen on microscopy. She may have developed her pulmonary infarction from a pulmonary embolus, possibly secondary to a deep venous thrombosis in her right leg, given the presence asymmetrical swelling in her right leg. Whilst the textbook description of pulmonary embolism is of abrupt onset of pain, this is often not the case and a substantial proportion of patients present with insidious onset of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung cancer \u003C/strong\u003Ecan present with a unilateral pleural effusion. Pleural fluid analysis usually demonstrates an exudate and is lymphocytic. It can be associated with malignant cells on cytology, although the diagnostic yield of pleural fluid cytology is limited. Her minimal smoking history and lack of constitutional symptoms make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has a history of previous ischaemic heart disease, can predispose her to developing \u003Cstrong\u003Ecardiac failure\u003C/strong\u003E. Cardiac failure usually causes bilateral pleural effusions and pleural fluid analysis is transudative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer bilateral knee joint pain is more consistent with osteoarthritis. \u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause joint pain and pleural effusions, but pleural fluid analysis demonstrates turbid fluid, exudative, and with lymphocytes or occasionally polymorphs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely as there is no consolidation seen on the chest X-ray, and the patient has no fever or cough. The pleural fluid characteristics would depend on the type of organism causing pneumonia, but usually the fluid would have either polymorphs or lymphocytes present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pleural fluid analysis demonstrating exudative, blood-stained pleural fluid with red blood cells is consistent with pulmonary infarction"],"references":["Mercer RM, Corcoran JP, Porcel JM, Rahman NM, Psallidas I. Interpreting pleural fluid results\u2002. Clin Med (Lond). 2019 May;19(3):213-217. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.19-3-213. PMID: 31092513; PMCID: PMC6542220.","Lat T, Paul M. Malignant Effusion. [Updated 2022 Oct 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519522/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40580"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40580"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T10:10:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T10:11:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4897"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55062"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medic